Walk-In Clinic
States she was beat up and has severe rib pain from pervious incident also wants to check if shes pregnant, she states she was coughing up blood as well
25 minutes or more were spent in the care of this patient, at least 50% of which was counseling and/or coordination of care.

11.26.19: patient is a 38-year-old RN with some significant psychosocial issues. She is a heavy alcoholic and has been in some very abusive relationships recently. About 2 weeks ago she was beat up by her significant other while they were drinking together. She was seen at the ER and found to be pregnant and thus x-rays and CT scans were not done. She was kept in the hospital, ICU, for a few days and then left. She tells a story of her significant other stealing her car with all of her stuff in it. She states she no longer has any identification as it was all in her vehicle. She also states that her car has not been found.
She has pain in her left ribs and abdomen and has been peeing blood since her assault. She would like to get the imaging that was recommended in the hospital.
She is not having any neurologic syndrome. No headache. No neck pain or stiffness. She does continue to drink heavily. His been in and out of women shelters.
discussion: We will get imaging as below. Patient is advised to stay away from significant other. She is unsure where he is at this point. She did press charges but thinks he is "on the lamb".
She is advised to go to the ER should symptoms worsen.
• XR, ribs, unilateral, w/ PA chest

We have discussed a large differential diagnosis for abdominal discomfort. Pt understands that without further workup, it will be hard to give a definitive dx. We have spoken about the acute abdomen as well as other types of abdominal pain at length. We have decided together to do an outpatient workup to help further elucidate that causes of patient's symptoms, as above. See workup below. Pt understands that I will do my best to contact them once labs/imaging results are available, but if sx worsen before I have results or before I can contact patient directly, they should go directly to the ER. Please see sx control measures/meds outlined below in orders. Pt agrees to re-check in 12-24 hours if persistent but not worsening symptoms despite tx.
She is advised to go to the ER should symptoms worsen.
• CT, abdomen + pelvis, w/ contrast - Abdominal Pain, Severe, hematuria after assault to back and abdomen

Is unclear why patient has microscopic hematuria and bilirubinuria and proteinuria. For these reasons we will check CMP and CBC. Patient follow-up with OB/GYN and PCP.
11.27.19: now has microscopic and gross hematuria. This is certainly possible that it is related to her assault. Please see imaging studies and labs above.

She was kept in the hospital, ICU, for a few days and then left. She tells a story of her significant other stealing her car with all of her stuff in it. She states she no longer has any identification as it was all in her vehicle. She also states that her car has not been found.

She has pain in her left ribs and abdomen and has been peeing blood since her assault. She would like to get the imaging that was recommended in the hospital.

She is not having any neurologic syndrome. No headache. No neck pain or stiffness. She does continue to drink heavily. His been in and out of women shelters.
